## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## vibe_review_alternating
##
## Alternating Claude / GPT code review with deterministic
## "two consecutive positive verdicts" stop condition. When a
## verdict is negative, apply fix-all in a fresh Claude session
## before retrying.
##
##   Loop 1: claude_code + opus 4.7
##   Loop 2: claw + gpt-5.5
##   Loop 3: like loop 1, alternating
##
## Stops when:
##   - 2 consecutive positive verdicts (Claude AND GPT both validate
##     in successive iterations of opposite families), OR
##   - max review_loop iterations reached
##
## False-positive resistance:
##   1. Reviewers self-rate their `confidence` (low/medium/high) and
##      are explicitly told to drop stylistic preferences.
##   2. The fixer can `pushback` on items it judges non-bloquant,
##      with a justification.
##   3. The next reviewer receives the prior pushback list and is
##      instructed to NOT re-flag those items unless evidence has
##      changed — this prevents a single false positive from
##      blocking the loop forever.
##   4. `streak_check` treats a low-confidence rejection as a
##      soft-approval (alternation continues, no fix is triggered).
##      Only medium/high-confidence rejections route to the fixer.
##
## Demonstrates four DSL features delivered together:
##   1. `round_robin` router for backend alternation
##   2. `compute` node for deterministic AND of current + previous
##      verdict (no LLM call, no shell-out)
##   3. `loop.<name>.previous_output` namespace eliminating manual
##      `previous_verdict` relay through every loop-bearing edge
##   4. Boolean expressions in `when` clauses (quoted form)
## ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

vars:
  workspace_dir: string = "${PROJECT_DIR}"
  scope_notes: string = ""

prompt review_system:
  Tu es un reviewer de code TRES exigeant et methodique
  en charge d'une revue PRODUCTION-READY GLOBALE — pas
  une revue de diff, pas une revue de "ce qui a change
  recemment", mais une revue complete du code en
  exploitation reelle.

  PERIMETRE DE LA REVUE (CRUCIAL) :
  1. Tu reviews TOUT le code dans le workspace, comme un
     SRE qui prend en charge le service. Le hash HEAD du
     git n'a aucun privilege — un bug introduit il y a
     six mois compte autant qu'un bug du dernier commit.
  2. NE TE LIMITE PAS aux derniers commits, au diff, ou
     aux fichiers que tu as touches lors d'iterations
     precedentes. `git log` peut servir d'orientation
     mais JAMAIS de perimetre.
  3. Couvre les axes production-ready :
       - Securite : auth, validation des entrees, fuites
         de secrets, injection (shell/SQL/template),
         path traversal, deserialisation non sure.
       - Robustesse : gestion d'erreur exhaustive, panics
         non rattrapes, goroutines fuyantes, race
         conditions, deadlocks, channels non bornes,
         timeouts manquants, retry sans backoff.
       - Donnees : migrations schema, integrite des
         indexes, transactions, idempotence, ordre de
         commit, perte de donnees sur crash.
       - Concurrence : mutex non equilibres, lock
         hierarchy, double-close, double-spawn,
         atomicity bugs.
       - Observabilite : logs structures, metrics,
         traces, signaux d'erreur perdus.
       - Performance : O(n^2) sur chemin chaud, memoire
         non bornee, cache miss systematique, requetes
         N+1.
       - Boundaries : reprise apres crash/panic,
         resilience aux entrees corrompues, comportement
         sur saturation.
  4. ITERATIONS — usage concret de l'historique :
     - Sur la premiere iteration, choisis 3-5 surfaces
       et fouille a fond.
     - Sur les iterations suivantes, choisis des
       surfaces NON COUVERTES par les iterations
       precedentes (utilise `previous_scanned_areas` en
       input). Les surfaces deja examinees sont, par
       defaut, considerees vetees.
     - Tu peux re-examiner une surface deja couverte
       UNIQUEMENT si tu as une nouvelle hypothese
       concrete a tester (preuve specifique d'un bug
       qui aurait ete rate).
     - Renseigne `scanned_areas` avec les paquets,
       fichiers, ou domaines que tu as effectivement
       audites cette iteration. Sois precis et concis.
  5. Le PRINCIPE D'ELARGISSEMENT s'applique : si tu n'as
     trouve aucun blocker apres avoir epuise les
     surfaces evidentes, ELARGIS — passe aux surfaces
     subtiles (concurrence, recovery, observabilite,
     entrees corrompues, edge cases). Ne donne pas
     `approved=true` simplement parce que la zone que tu
     as regardee est propre. Approved=true exige que la
     COUVERTURE CUMULATIVE entre les iterations soit
     suffisante.

  REGLES ANTI FAUX-POSITIFS :
  1. Ne marque approved=false que pour des problemes
     reellement bloquants pour la production : bugs,
     regressions, vulnerabilites de securite, code mort
     evident. Les preferences stylistiques, le naming,
     les optimisations mineures, la documentation
     manquante ne sont PAS des blockers.
  2. Auto-critique : pour chaque blocker que tu envisages,
     demande-toi "est-ce REELLEMENT bloquant en production
     ou est-ce une preference personnelle ?" Si tu hesites,
     ce n'est PAS un blocker — au mieux un point de
     vigilance non bloquant.
  3. Confiance : evalue ta propre certitude.
       - "high" = tu peux pointer la ligne exacte et
         expliquer le scenario de production qui casse
       - "medium" = tu vois un probleme probable mais pas
         100% sur du contexte
       - "low" = doute, intuition, pas de preuve concrete
  4. Si une review precedente (de l'autre famille) a juge
     ce code OK SUR DES SURFACES PRECISES, sois EXTRA
     strict avant d'ajouter de nouveaux blockers SUR CES
     MEMES surfaces — il faut une preuve concrete que
     l'autre reviewer a ratee. Mais sur des surfaces
     NON couvertes precedemment, repars a froid.
  5. Items deja pushbackes par le fixer : ne les
     re-flague PAS sauf si tu as une preuve nouvelle.

  ESCALADE HUMAINE :
  Quand tu rencontres une AMBIGUITE qu'aucune lecture du
  code ne peut resoudre (ex : "ce comportement est-il
  intentionnel ?", "la spec dit-elle X ou Y ?", "dois-je
  preserver la rétrocompatibilité ?"), appelle le tool
  `ask_user` avec ta question precise. Le run sera mis en
  pause, la question s'affichera dans le terminal du dev,
  et tu seras re-invoque avec sa reponse injectee dans
  ton contexte (un bloc "[PRIOR INTERACTION]" sera
  prepended a ton prompt utilisateur).

  Utilise cette escalade avec parcimonie : seulement
  quand tu ne peux PAS trancher sans information
  humaine. Pour les jugements techniques ordinaires,
  tranche toi-meme et baisse `confidence` si tu n'es pas
  sur.

prompt review_user_claude:
  Review le code dans {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Notes de portee :
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Iteration courante : {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  Verdict du reviewer precedent (l'autre famille,
  iteration immediatement avant — vide si premiere
  iteration) :
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Surfaces deja auditees lors d'iterations precedentes
  (toutes familles confondues — utilisees pour orienter
  ta couverture differente, pas pour limiter ta
  rigueur) :
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items deja pushbackes par le fixer (NE PAS RE-FLAGUER
  sans preuve nouvelle) :
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Justification du pushback precedent :
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Produis un verdict structure :
    - approved: true UNIQUEMENT si la couverture
      cumulative entre les iterations est suffisante
      ET aucun blocker n'a ete trouve — pas si tu n'as
      regarde qu'une partie du code.
    - family: "claude" pour ce reviewer
    - blockers: liste des problemes vraiment bloquants
      (apres auto-critique — exclure les preferences)
    - fix_plan: plan d'action concret pour fixer les blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: paquets / fichiers / surfaces que
      tu as effectivement audites CETTE iteration
      (texte concis : ex. "pkg/runtime/engine.go (recovery dispatch)",
      ".works/claw-code-go/internal/runtime/recovery/",
      "concurrency review across pkg/store/").
      Sera relaye au prochain reviewer.

prompt review_user_gpt:
  Review le code dans {{vars.workspace_dir}}.

  Notes de portee :
  {{vars.scope_notes}}

  Iteration courante : {{loop.review_loop.iteration}}/{{loop.review_loop.max}}

  Verdict du reviewer precedent (l'autre famille,
  iteration immediatement avant — vide si premiere
  iteration) :
  {{loop.review_loop.previous_output}}

  Surfaces deja auditees lors d'iterations precedentes
  (toutes familles confondues — utilisees pour orienter
  ta couverture differente, pas pour limiter ta
  rigueur) :
  {{input.previous_scanned_areas}}

  Items deja pushbackes par le fixer (NE PAS RE-FLAGUER
  sans preuve nouvelle) :
  {{input.prior_pushback}}

  Justification du pushback precedent :
  {{input.prior_pushback_justification}}

  Produis un verdict structure :
    - approved: true UNIQUEMENT si la couverture
      cumulative entre les iterations est suffisante
      ET aucun blocker n'a ete trouve — pas si tu n'as
      regarde qu'une partie du code.
    - family: "gpt" pour ce reviewer
    - blockers: liste des problemes vraiment bloquants
      (apres auto-critique — exclure les preferences)
    - fix_plan: plan d'action concret pour fixer les blockers
    - confidence: "low" / "medium" / "high"
    - scanned_areas: paquets / fichiers / surfaces que
      tu as effectivement audites CETTE iteration
      (texte concis). Sera relaye au prochain reviewer.

prompt fix_system:
  Tu es un developpeur expert. Tu corriges les problemes
  bloquants signales par un reviewer en appliquant des
  modifications concretes au code.

  Tu peux REFUSER un item de la liste de blockers si tu
  juges qu'il n'est pas reellement bloquant pour la
  production (preference stylistique, optimisation
  mineure, doc manquante, etc.). Liste ces items dans
  `pushback` avec une justification dans
  `pushback_justification`. Le prochain reviewer sera
  instruit de NE PAS re-flaguer ces items, evitant qu'un
  faux positif fasse boucler le workflow indefiniment.

  Utilise pushback avec parcimonie : si tu pushbackes
  tout, le code ne sera jamais ameliore.

  ESCALADE HUMAINE :
  Si un blocker est reellement ambigu (la spec ne dit pas
  comment le resoudre, plusieurs approches valides
  s'opposent, etc.), appelle le tool `ask_user` avec ta
  question precise. Le run se met en pause, la question
  s'affiche dans le terminal du dev, et tu seras
  re-invoque avec la reponse en contexte. N'utilise pas
  cette voie pour des choix techniques que tu peux
  trancher seul.

prompt fix_user:
  Pour le code dans {{vars.workspace_dir}}, examine cette
  liste de blockers et applique des fixes concrets.

  Blockers signales :
  {{input.blockers}}

  Plan de fix propose :
  {{input.fix_plan}}

  Pour CHAQUE blocker :
    - Si c'est un vrai probleme bloquant production :
      lis le fichier concerne, applique la correction,
      verifie que les tests passent.
    - Si tu juges que ce n'est PAS bloquant (preference
      stylistique, optimisation mineure, etc.) : ajoute
      l'item exact a `pushback` avec une justification
      claire dans `pushback_justification`.

  En sortie :
    - applied: true si au moins un fix a ete applique
    - summary: resume des fixes appliques
    - pushback: items refuses (vide si tous fixes)
    - pushback_justification: explication du pushback

## ─── Schemas ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

schema review_input:
  prior_pushback: string[]
  prior_pushback_justification: string
  ## previous_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from
  ## ALL prior reviewer iterations (both families). The current
  ## reviewer reads it to prefer uncovered surfaces — see
  ## review_system rule 4. Empty on the first iteration.
  previous_scanned_areas: string[]

schema verdict_output:
  approved: bool
  ## family is enum-constrained: a model that hallucinates a third
  ## value (we observed gpt-5.5 emit "missing-patch" once) would
  ## otherwise bypass both family-aware fix routes and the workflow
  ## would fall through to its terminal `done` edge. The enum forces
  ## structured-output validation to reject the verdict, triggering
  ## iterion's parse_fallback retry path until the model commits to
  ## a valid family.
  family: string [enum: "claude", "gpt"]
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  confidence: string [enum: "low", "medium", "high"]
  ## scanned_areas captures the surfaces this reviewer actually
  ## audited this iteration (e.g. "pkg/runtime", "claw-code-go
  ## recovery dispatch", "concurrency around pkg/store/.lock").
  ## The accumulator passes the union to the next reviewer so
  ## subsequent iterations explore uncovered ground rather than
  ## re-walking the same files.
  scanned_areas: string[]

## streak_check relays approved/blockers/fix_plan/family from its
## input (the current reviewer's verdict) and computes a
## deterministic stop signal based on the previous reviewer's
## verdict. The `family` passthrough lets the fix routing pick the
## same-family fixer so the fix session can inherit the reviewer's
## context (and benefit from prompt-cache hits).
##
## Soft-approval: a low-confidence rejection (`approved=false` AND
## `confidence=="low"`) is treated as approved for streak/fix
## routing purposes. The reviewer's own uncertainty isn't a strong
## enough signal to trigger a fix cycle and risk a false-positive
## loop.
##
## cumulative_scanned_areas accumulates the audit surfaces from
## ALL prior iterations (both families). The accumulator pattern
## relies on `outputs.streak_check` resolving to the PREVIOUS
## iteration's output during the current expression evaluation
## (rs.outputs is updated AFTER execCompute completes), so the
## expression `unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas,
## input.scanned_areas))` produces a monotonically growing union.
## On the first iteration `outputs.streak_check` is nil → concat
## treats it as empty → result == unique(input.scanned_areas).
schema streak_state:
  stop: bool
  approved: bool
  family: string
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string
  cumulative_scanned_areas: string[]

schema fix_input:
  blockers: string[]
  fix_plan: string

schema fix_output:
  applied: bool
  summary: string
  pushback: string[]
  pushback_justification: string

## ─── Nodes ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

router alt:
  mode: round_robin

judge reviewer_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  reasoning_effort: extra_high
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_claude
  session: fresh
  ## When the LLM hits genuine uncertainty (ambiguous spec, missing
  ## context, impossible-to-decide trade-off), it can escalate to
  ## the human running the CLI by emitting `_needs_interaction:
  ## true` + `_interaction_questions: {...}` in its JSON output.
  ## The runtime catches this, pauses, prompts the dev in their
  ## terminal, and re-invokes the reviewer with the answer mapped
  ## into its input — preserving session continuity.
  interaction: human

judge reviewer_gpt:
  model: "openai/gpt-5.5"
  input: review_input
  output: verdict_output
  system: review_system
  user: review_user_gpt
  session: fresh
  ## claw backend uses snake_case tool names. Without these the
  ## reviewer can't read the workspace and produces a
  ## "no filesystem access" verdict — the claw runtime exposes
  ## these via tool.RegisterClawBuiltins.
  tools: [bash, read_file, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  interaction: human

## Deterministic streak detector.
##
## stop=true iff (current AND previous reviewer both ACTUALLY
## approved) AND families differ. The success criterion is two
## consecutive POSITIVE verdicts from opposite families — both
## AIs must let the code pass on successive iterations. A
## low-confidence rejection does NOT count as approval for the
## stop signal: the code only ships when it convinces both
## reviewers.
##
## The `approved` passthrough field stays soft — it includes
## low-confidence rejections — so the downstream
## `when approved` edge keeps alternating without invoking the
## fixer when a reviewer is merely uncertain. This separation
## means the workflow keeps cycling without forced fix attempts
## on flaky-low-confidence rejections, but requires real
## approvals to terminate.
compute streak_check:
  output: streak_state
  expr:
    stop: "input.approved && loop.review_loop.previous_output.approved && input.family != loop.review_loop.previous_output.family"
    approved: "input.approved || input.confidence == 'low'"
    family: "input.family"
    blockers: "input.blockers"
    fix_plan: "input.fix_plan"
    cumulative_scanned_areas: "unique(concat(outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas, input.scanned_areas))"

## Per-family fixers. Each one inherits the SAME-family reviewer's
## session via `session: inherit` + `_session_id` mapping on the
## edge — so the fixer reuses the prompt cache, the workspace files
## already loaded, and the reviewer's reasoning chain. The result
## is one session per loop iteration per family (not two), which
## both shortens latency and dramatically reduces token cost:
## without inheritance every fixer would re-scan the workspace.
agent fix_claude:
  backend: "claude_code"
  model: "claude-opus-4-7"
  reasoning_effort: extra_high
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## Same escalation contract as the reviewers — the fixer can ask
  ## the dev a question (e.g. clarify the intent of an ambiguous
  ## blocker) instead of guessing.
  interaction: human

agent fix_gpt:
  model: "openai/gpt-5.5"
  input: fix_input
  output: fix_output
  system: fix_system
  user: fix_user
  session: inherit
  ## claw needs the same read/write toolset the reviewer used so
  ## the fixer can actually apply edits.
  tools: [bash, read_file, write_file, file_edit, glob, grep]
  tool_max_steps: 30
  interaction: human

## ─── Workflow ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

workflow vibe_review_alternating:
  entry: alt

  budget:
    max_parallel_branches: 1
    max_duration: "2h"
    max_cost_usd: 60

  ## Round-robin alternates: 1st pass → claude, 2nd → gpt, repeat.
  ## Each reviewer receives the OTHER family's most recent fixer
  ## pushback so it knows which items to skip — the alternation
  ## guarantees the cross-family pushback comes from the previous
  ## iteration's fixer of the opposing family. On the first
  ## iteration both `outputs.fix_*` are empty → fields render as
  ## empty strings and the prompt's "ne re-flague pas ces items"
  ## section is harmless.
  alt -> reviewer_claude with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_gpt.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}"
  }
  alt -> reviewer_gpt with {
    prior_pushback: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback}}",
    prior_pushback_justification: "{{outputs.fix_claude.pushback_justification}}",
    previous_scanned_areas: "{{outputs.streak_check.cumulative_scanned_areas}}"
  }

  ## Both reviewers feed into streak_check. The loop is attached
  ## here so the runtime snapshots the reviewer's verdict as
  ## `loop.review_loop.previous_output` for the NEXT iteration to
  ## inspect — eliminating the manual `previous_verdict` relay.
  reviewer_claude -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude.confidence}}"
  }
  reviewer_gpt -> streak_check as review_loop(15) with {
    approved: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.approved}}",
    family: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.family}}",
    blockers: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.fix_plan}}",
    confidence: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt.confidence}}"
  }

  ## Stop when streak detected (cross-family double approval).
  streak_check -> done when stop

  ## Otherwise approved (no streak yet, OR low-confidence rejection
  ## treated as soft-approved): keep alternating without fixing.
  ## Expression form is shown here both to demonstrate the new
  ## syntax and so future authors can extend the predicate (e.g.
  ## tighten the soft-approval condition) by enriching the
  ## quoted expression.
  ##
  ## NOTE: this edge does NOT carry `review_loop` so the loop
  ## counter (and the previous_output snapshot) is incremented
  ## ONCE per cycle on the reviewer→streak_check edge above. The
  ## cycle is still bounded because that edge IS loop-bearing.
  streak_check -> alt when "approved"

  ## Medium/high-confidence rejection: route to the SAME-family
  ## fixer so it can inherit the reviewer's session (one session
  ## per iteration per family — see fix_claude / fix_gpt comments).
  ## `_session_id` reads directly from the most recent reviewer
  ## output rather than going through streak_check, because compute
  ## passthrough strips the underscore-prefixed metadata fields.
  ##
  ## Edge order matters: iterion evaluates conditional edges top-
  ## down, first match wins. We list both family-specific fixers
  ## before the unconditional `done` fallthrough so loop-exhaustion
  ## still terminates cleanly.
  streak_check -> fix_claude when "!approved && family == 'claude'" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_claude._session_id}}"
  }
  streak_check -> fix_gpt when "!approved && family == 'gpt'" with {
    blockers: "{{outputs.streak_check.blockers}}",
    fix_plan: "{{outputs.streak_check.fix_plan}}",
    _session_id: "{{outputs.reviewer_gpt._session_id}}"
  }

  ## Recovery cycle uses a separate loop name so its counter doesn't
  ## interfere with the review_loop snapshot semantics. Sized large
  ## enough to allow review_loop to be the binding constraint. Both
  ## fixers share the loop counter — total fix attempts across both
  ## families are capped at 20.
  fix_claude -> alt as recovery_loop(20)
  fix_gpt    -> alt as recovery_loop(20)

  ## Loop exhaustion fallbacks: when a bounded loop hits its limit
  ## the loop-bearing edges above are skipped and execution falls
  ## through to these unconditional terminal edges.
  reviewer_claude -> done
  reviewer_gpt    -> done
  fix_claude      -> done
  fix_gpt         -> done
  ## streak_check's catch-all routes back to `alt` (not `done`) so
  ## an unmatched conditional state (e.g. a hallucinated family that
  ## escapes the enum, or any future expression edge case) keeps
  ## the loop cycling rather than silently terminating. The bounded
  ## review_loop counter on the reviewer→streak_check edges still
  ## guarantees the workflow eventually exits — exhaustion routes
  ## via the reviewer→done fallthrough above.
  streak_check    -> alt
